From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Your Name <your.email@example.com>
Date: Tue, 10 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] ANDROID: stop_machine: all-CPU self-dump at 8s +
 panic at 10s on migration deadlock

Problem
-------
On Qualcomm platforms running Android16/GKI (Linux 6.12, Clang 19,
CONFIG_HZ=250, CONFIG_NO_HZ_IDLE=y), migration/N threads deadlock inside
multi_cpu_stop(). Two confirmed patterns:

  Pattern A -- nested re-entrancy (LB path):
    active_load_balance_cpu_stop()
      -> finish_task_switch() -> run_balance_callbacks()
        -> sched_balance_rq() -> stop_one_cpu_nowait()
    while already executing inside stop_two_cpus() / multi_cpu_stop().
    Signature in Sec6: one CPU is_active=YES, others is_active=NO.

  Pattern B -- concurrent stop_machine exhaustion:
    N concurrent stop_machine() calls (e.g. aarch64_insn_patch_text_cb
    racing with LB or other callers) exhaust all cpu_stopper threads.
    Callback issues nested stop_machine() which cannot be serviced.
    Signature in Sec6: ALL CPUs show is_active=YES.

The Qualcomm msm_watchdog bark fires at ~11s. This patch detects the
deadlock at 3s, collects all-CPU call stacks within 8s, and panics at
10s -- capturing a clean ramdump before the watchdog fires.

==========================================================================
Design: self-dump on each CPU + ktime-bounded wait + panic at 10s
==========================================================================

Why self-dump instead of trigger_all_cpu_backtrace() IPI:
  trigger_all_cpu_backtrace() sends IPI_CPU_BACKTRACE to each CPU and
  waits up to 10 seconds for each response. CPUs in DISABLE_IRQ state
  have local IRQs disabled -- the IPI cannot be delivered -- so the
  caller blocks for 10s per unresponsive CPU. On an 8-core device this
  can be 70s, far beyond the 11s watchdog bark. Ref:
  patchew.org/linux/fb0b7a92-d371-4510-80c4-25a57f2c4f3d@paulmck-laptop/

  Self-dump: each CPU that detects the timeout (IRQs ON = PREPARE state)
  calls dump_stack() on itself before entering the wait spin. No IPI.
  No cross-CPU wait. Bounded time.

  CPUs in DISABLE_IRQ state cannot detect the timeout (jiffies frozen,
  time_after() false) and therefore cannot self-dump. The owner logs a
  timeout message for those CPUs. Their stacks are fully preserved in
  the ramdump captured by panic().

Timeline:
  T=0s    deadlock begins

  T=3s    time_after() fires on PREPARE-state CPUs (IRQs ON, jiffies live)
          Phase 1 (ALL detecting CPUs, before cmpxchg):
            stopper_snapshot_self() -- write own percpu slot
            dump_stack()            -- capture own call stack NOW
            atomic_set(stopper_dump_done, 1) -- mark self complete

          atomic_cmpxchg(&stopper_dump_owner, -1, cpu):
            ONE CPU wins  --> dump owner: runs Sec1-6 + waits + panics
            ALL others    --> enter spin: while(1) cpu_relax() +
                              touch_nmi_watchdog()

  T=3s    Sec1: owner outer stopper fn + caller       (<50ms)
  T=3s    Sec2: multi_stop_data state                 (<50ms)
  T=3s    Sec3: CPU masks                             (<50ms)
  T=3s    Sec4: owner stopper state (detailed)        (<100ms)

  T=3-8s  Sec5: owner polls stopper_dump_done for all online CPUs.
                PREPARE CPUs: already set done in Phase 1 -> instant.
                DISABLE_IRQ CPUs: never set done (jiffies frozen, cannot
                  detect) -> owner waits up to dump deadline then logs:
                  "[CPU%u] dump timeout: IRQs disabled -- see ramdump"
                ktime_get() used for deadline (hardware monotonic counter,
                  reads ARM hardware counter directly, IRQ-independent,
                  safe even when local jiffies are frozen).

  T=8s    Sec6: print all percpu snapshots (from Phase 1 writers)
  T=8s    spin touching watchdog until T=10s panic deadline

  T=10s   panic() -- ramdump captured
            All PREPARE-CPU stacks: in kmsg above (from Phase 1 dumps)
            All DISABLE_IRQ-CPU stacks: in ramdump
  T=11s   Qualcomm bark_time -- 1s margin

==========================================================================
Per-CPU dump done tracking (stopper_dump_done)
==========================================================================

DEFINE_PER_CPU(atomic_t, stopper_dump_done) -- zero-initialised at boot.

Writer (each detecting CPU in Phase 1):
  dump_stack();
  atomic_set(this_cpu_ptr(&stopper_dump_done), 1);

Reader (dump owner in Sec5 wait loop):
  atomic_read(per_cpu_ptr(&stopper_dump_done, c))

No explicit barrier needed between dump_stack() and atomic_set():
  dump_stack() is a non-trivial sequence of pr_emerg/printk calls that
  act as implicit barriers. atomic_set() on ARM64 is a plain store with
  no ordering requirement here because the owner only needs to see the
  SIDE EFFECT (kmsg output) of dump_stack(), not its memory writes.
  The kmsg ring buffer has its own internal serialization.

==========================================================================
Timing constants
==========================================================================

  STOPPER_TIMEOUT_JIFFIES  = 3 * HZ  (~3000ms at HZ=250)
    jiffies-based detection threshold. Fires in PREPARE state (IRQs ON).
    In DISABLE_IRQ/RUN: jiffies frozen, time_after() false. No false fire.

  STOPPER_DUMP_WINDOW_MS   = 5000ULL
    ktime window from detection for all-CPU dump collection.
    T=3s + 5s = T=8s from deadlock start.

  STOPPER_PANIC_WINDOW_MS  = 7000ULL
    ktime window from detection to panic().
    T=3s + 7s = T=10s from deadlock start.
    Qualcomm bark_time ~11s -> 1s margin.

==========================================================================
Code placement -- two insertion points (Clang 19 build correctness)
==========================================================================

INSERT POINT A (after includes, before struct cpu_stopper ~line 180):
  STOPPER_TIMEOUT_JIFFIES, STOPPER_DUMP_WINDOW_MS, STOPPER_PANIC_WINDOW_MS
  stopper_dump_owner, stopper_dump_done
  struct stopper_cpu_snapshot, DEFINE_PER_CPU(stopper_snapshot)
  stopper_snapshot_self()
  -- NOTHING here references cpu_stopper (the percpu var) or its struct.
     stopper_snapshot_self() receives fn+caller as void*/ulong parameters.

INSERT POINT B (after struct multi_stop_data ~line 210):
  stopper_state_names[], stopper_state_name()
  stopper_dump_one_cpu()      -- uses per_cpu_ptr(&cpu_stopper, cpu)
  stopper_dump_msdata()       -- uses struct multi_stop_data *
  stopper_wait_for_cpu_dumps() -- polls stopper_dump_done, ktime bounded
  stopper_print_other_snapshots() -- reads stopper_snapshot percpu slots
  stopper_deadlock_dump()     -- uses this_cpu_ptr(&cpu_stopper)
  -- All types fully defined here.

==========================================================================
Fix 1: int cpu -> unsigned int cpu (retained from production patch)
==========================================================================

smp_processor_id() returns 'unsigned int'. Clang 19 warns on signed/
unsigned mismatch at cpumask_test_cpu() and per_cpu_ptr() call sites.

==========================================================================
Fix 2: Position C unconditional detection (retained from production patch)
==========================================================================

  do {
    if (curstate < msdata->state) { ... }
    if (is_active)       ack_state(msdata);         /* A */
    else if (curstate > MULTI_STOP_PREPARE) {
        touch_nmi_watchdog(); rcu_momentary_eqs();  /* B: not in PREPARE */
    }
    /* C: ALL CPUs, ALL states, every iteration -- our detection point */
    if (!timed_out && time_after(now_j, ...)) { ... }
  } while (curstate != MULTI_STOP_EXIT);

rcu_momentary_eqs() requires IRQs disabled (caller contract). In PREPARE
state position B is never reached (condition false), so IRQs stay ON and
jiffies advance. In DISABLE_IRQ/RUN: position B IS reached, IRQs are off,
jiffies frozen, time_after() false -- no false positive.

==========================================================================
Android GKI compliance
==========================================================================

- Single file: kernel/stop_machine.c only
- No new exported symbols, no new Kconfig options
- Clang 19 / LLD 19 compatible
- ktime_get(): <linux/ktime.h> -- newly added include
- atomic_t / atomic_set / atomic_read: <linux/atomic.h> -- already present
- DEFINE_PER_CPU: <linux/percpu.h> -- already present
- No trigger_all_cpu_backtrace() (IPI hazard with DISABLE_IRQ CPUs)

